**Change Runtime**  
Runtimes are virtual machines that run your notebook, store temp files, and execute code.   
Because ML models use a lot of computing power, you want to use a runtime environment that can handle Meridian. There are generally terms for these environments: Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) or a Tensor Processing Unit (TPU)

**Meridian recommends the T4 GPU** as it has an NVIDIA GPU. NVIDIA GPUs have specialized architectures and software libraries (like CUDA and cuDNN) that are highly optimized for deep learning tasks. 

CPU is going to be too basic for Meridian and will most likely crash out no matter how small of a model you run in Meridian. 

v2-8 TPU is for the fastest performance with TensorFlow models, especially large ones. Be aware that it's most optimized for the TensorFlow ecosystem. I have not tried it yet\!

**Pip install.**   
Pip stands for Pip Installs Packages or Preferred Installer Program. Think of it as the package manager for Python.

Imagine you're building with LEGOs. You have your basic bricks, but sometimes you need specialized pieces – maybe a specific type of connector, a wheel, or a miniature figure – that aren't in your standard collection. Pip install allows you to purchase all of the parts you need to build our model. 

That's where pip comes in for Python. Python has a vast ecosystem of third-party libraries and frameworks (like google-meridian in your previous example) that extend its capabilities far beyond the built-in functions. Pip is the tool that allows you to easily find, download, install, and manage these external packages from a central repository called the Python Package Index (PyPI).

A pip file might have information like this:

This is the time increment we want to track. The demo data track advertising and sales from early 2021 \- 2024\. If you look at the data, you will notice that they only have one date for each week, so they are rolling up the data weekly. This is really great if you are B2B.

**controls=\['GQV', 'Competitor\_Sales'\],**  
Controls are confounding variables that you and I don’t control. These are very critical and help you understand your market. Inexplicable, Google expects us to have day-by-day or week-by-week competitor sales. Maybe you all are much more fortunate than I am, but I can’t expect to have this in real life. 

That being said, GQV is pretty awesome, as it shows how popular your keywords are over time regardless of how much you were spending. That being said, from what I learned, Google Ads is not super linear in terms of value. There seems to be “levels” you need to unlock to get more access to users. This is why I recommend having a long term testing period where you might spend very little for a few weeks, spend very high for a few weeks, and average for other weeks. I honestly believe that will not only help you find the “levels” for your industry, but should help the model see different scenarios. If you spend $1,000 every day on Google Ads for years, it is going to be really hard to see the effectiveness of Google Ads, because we don’t know what it looks like without Google Ads.

**roi\_mu \= 0.2**     
**roi\_sigma \= 0.9**  
roi\_mu of 0.2 a somewhat wrong, but useful model,  is that we expect we make 20% profit for every $1 we spend. This line defines a variable roi\_mu and sets its value to 0.2. This variable represents the mean (μ) of the prior distribution we will use for the Return On Investment (ROI) of each media channel. In reality, the number is much more complicated than that. 

roi\_sigma \= 0.9 is that we are not sure about our ROI.  A higher number (close to 1\) indicates we are not very sure about our roi\_mu value.this line defines roi\_sigma and sets it to 0.9. This represents the standard deviation (σ) of the prior distribution for the ROI of each media channel.

A good example I have is google ads. If we believe that Google Ads has an ROI of 2, but we are not super sure. We could have a sigma of 0.3 and a mu of 0.648.  
A really cool tool for this can be found here: [https://homepage.divms.uiowa.edu/\~mbognar/applets/lognormal.html](https://homepage.divms.uiowa.edu/~mbognar/applets/lognormal.html)  
In this, E(x) is what I believe is your actual ROI, and you can play around with mean and st dev to find the best combination to get the results you expect.

Below, with a mean of 2 and st dev of .3 my ROI might be close to 7.7\! 

![][image2]

The biggest issue here is that it is treating all channels the same, and we know our real data will not behave like that. Because of this, in your real data, you will define your mean and standard deviation for each channel.

) \# This creates a list of channel-ordered (mu, sigma) tuples.

In this example, you would define the mean and standard deviation for each channel into this tuple, then, the zip function would assign everything for Meridian. 

**prior \= prior\_distribution.PriorDistribution(**  
**roi\_m=tfp.distributions.LogNormal(roi\_mu, roi\_sigma, name=constants.ROI\_M)**   
This uses the LogNormal distribution from the TensorFlow Probability (TFP) library. A LogNormal distribution is often used for positive-valued parameters like ROI because it ensures that the sampled values will always be greater than zero. (ROI should never be negative\!)

The first two arguments, roi\_mu and roi\_sigma, are the parameters of the underlying Normal distribution whose exponentiation gives the LogNormal distribution. It's important to note that these are not the mean and standard deviation of the LogNormal distribution itself.  
name=constants.ROI\_M assigns a specific name (ROI\_M) to this prior distribution within the Meridian model, which helps in identifying and managing it later.

I don’t have any recommendations for this part, so I just stick with the default settings in my models.

%%time  
mmm.sample\_prior(500)  
mmm.sample\_posterior(n\_chains=7, n\_adapt=500, n\_burnin=500, n\_keep=1000, seed=1)

This takes between 7 \- 12 minutes in my experience for the demo. Colab seems to time out after 15 minutes, so be cautious on the values you have.  

**%%time**  
This is a Jupyter Notebook magic command that measures and displays the execution time of the cell. This helps us understand how long this step takes. 

**mmm:** This is the variable holding the Meridian model object, initialized earlier with your data and model specifications.

**mmm.sample\_prior(500)**  
This is how many different variations of the parameters Meridian will use to start the process. Imagine you're trying to guess how many candies are in a jar. Before you get any clues, you have some initial guess (your prior belief). sample\_prior(500) is like writing down 500 different guesses based on your initial hunch. These guesses will likely be spread out, reflecting your uncertainty. Later, when you get more information (data), you'll refine these guesses.

For each parameter in your model, it randomly draws a value from that parameter's prior distribution. It collects these randomly drawn values for all parameters into a single sample.  
It repeats this process 500 times, giving you 500 independent samples. This all happens before Meridan even looks at our data.

Technically, you could run a model using only the prior distribution in a Bayesian framework, but it would have significant limitations and wouldn't be very useful in most real-world scenarios as you don’t know what really happened. 

**mmm.sample\_posterior(n\_chains=7, n\_adapt=500, n\_burnin=500, n\_keep=1000, seed=1)**

The posterior distribution beings a refinement of the prior distribution based on the observed data. 

**n\_chains=7 means Meridian initiates 7 parallel and independent MCMC simulations**  
Imagine 7 boats starting at slightly different points on a lake (your prior). They are all trying to find the deepest part of the lake (the highest likelihood). If the lake has a very clear and obvious deep spot, all the boats will eventually be drawn to it, regardless of their starting point. However, if the lake has multiple smaller deep spots or a very gradually sloping bottom, the starting points might influence which "deep" area each boat ends up exploring. Running multiple boats helps you get a better sense of the overall depth profile.

**n\_adapt=500:** This refers to the adaptation or warm-up phase for each chain. During these first 500 iterations, the algorithm is trying to "tune" its sampling process to efficiently explore the posterior distribution. It's adjusting things like the step size to ensure it's not jumping around too wildly or getting stuck in one place. The results from this phase are typically discarded.

Imagine the algorithm is trying to find the regions in the parameter space that have high probability (like trying to find the peaks of a hilly landscape in the dark). To do this, it takes "steps" to new potential parameter values. Small steps might mean you never leave the little hill you start on. Large steps mean you jump around so much you might find the highest hill, but you probably don’t find the peak. 

For marketing data, this might be how long we see ads influencing sales after they have been seen. Maybe we think the effect is 1-2 weeks, but it could be faster or slower in many cases. This allows the model to run through all kinds of different options and hone in on the most consistent over time. 

**n\_keep=1000**: This specifies that after the adaptation and burn-in phases, the algorithm should keep 1000 samples from each of the 7 chains. These are the samples that will be used to approximate the posterior distribution – our updated beliefs about the model's parameters.

**seed=1**: This sets a random seed for the process. This is important for reproducibility. If you run the same model with the same data and the same seed, you should get the same results.

This code snippet is focused on checking the convergence of the Meridian model, which is a crucial step in Bayesian analysis. Convergence essentially means that the model has stabilized and is providing reliable estimates.

visualizer.ModelDiagnostics(mmm): This is the part that actually creates the diagnostic tools.

**R-hat and Convergence**  
R-hat is a key diagnostic for convergence in Bayesian models.

Ideal R-hat: Values very close to 1.0 indicate good convergence, meaning the different parts of the model are in agreement.  
Acceptable R-hat: Values below 1.2 are often considered acceptable, suggesting approximate convergence.  
Problematic R-hat: Values significantly above 1.2 raise concerns about convergence, indicating that the model may not have stabilized and the results may be unreliable.

**Convergence** in the context of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, which are used by Meridian, essentially means that all the different chains in the model have reached a similar and stable distribution of estimated parameters. Convergence is crucial for obtaining trustworthy estimates of the model's parameters and, consequently, reliable insights from the model's results.

plot\_model\_fit() just shows the results of each parameter in a box plot. 

A box plot, also known as a box-and-whisker plot, is a standardized way of visually representing the distribution of a dataset based on its five-number summary:   

Minimum: The lowest value in the dataset (excluding outliers).  
First Quartile (Q1): The value below which 25% of the data falls. It's the median of the lower half of the data.     
Median (Q2): The middle value of the dataset. 50% of the data points are below this value, and 50% are above it. It divides the dataset into two equal halves.     
Third Quartile (Q3): The value below which 75% of the data falls. It's the median of the upper half of the data.     
Maximum: The highest value in the dataset (excluding outliers).     
Here's how these values are typically displayed in a box plot:

* A box is drawn from the first quartile (Q1) to the third quartile (Q3). This box contains the middle 50% of the data, which is also known as the interquartile range (IQR).     
* A vertical line inside the box indicates the median (Q2).     
* Whiskers extend from each end of the box to the minimum and maximum values that are within a certain range (typically 1.5 times the IQR).     
* Any data points that fall outside the whiskers are considered outliers and are usually plotted as individual points (dots or asterisks).   

![][image3]

**In summary, a box plot provides a quick visual summary of:**  
Central Tendency: The median shows where the center of the data lies.     
Spread or Dispersion: The length of the box (IQR) indicates the variability of the middle 50% of the data. The length of the whiskers gives an idea of the overall spread.  
Skewness: The position of the median within the box and the relative lengths of the whiskers can suggest whether the data is symmetric or skewed (leaning towards higher or lower values).     
Outliers: Individual points outside the whiskers highlight potential unusual values in the dataset.’

**Run R-squared, MAPE, and wMAPE metrics**  
Goodness of fit metrics can be used as a confidence check that the model structure is appropriate and not overparameterized. ModelDiagnostics calculate R-Squared, MAPE, and wMAPE goodness of fit metrics.   
![][image5]  
If holdout\_id is set in Meridian, then R-squared, MAPE and wMAPE are also calculated for the Train and Test subsets. Be aware that goodness of fit metrics are a measure of predictive accuracy, which is not typically the goal of an MMM. However, these metrics still serve as a useful confidence check.

Values between 0 and 1 represent the proportion of the variance explained by the model. For example, an R-squared of 0.75 means that 75% of the variation in the dependent variable can be predicted from the independent variable(s).

R-squared should really needs to be close to 0.5 to have value. If your score is negative, you have a big problem, and it is likely your data is not very predictive. Generally, more data over time and more organic and promo channels will help track down these unknown trends. BUT Adding more independent variables to a model will always increase the R-squared, even if those variables are not truly related to the dependent variable. This can lead to overfitting. Adjusted R-squared attempts to correct for this by penalizing the addition of unnecessary variables.

R-squared does not indicate if a model is biased. A high R-squared can still occur with a poorly specified model.

MAPE is a measure of the accuracy of a forecasting method. It calculates the average absolute percentage difference between the actual values and the forecasted values. MAPE is expressed as a percentage, making it easy to understand. For example, a MAPE of 5% means that, on average, the forecast is off by 5% from the actual values. Lower MAPE values indicate higher accuracy.

A MAPE below 30% Is good IMO. 

wMAPE is a variation of MAPE that addresses some of its limitations by assigning weights to the errors. The weights are typically based on the actual values or some other measure of importance. So, generally, I would use wMAPE vs MAPE if they are different. 

**Revenue or KPI contribution —--\-![][image6]**

The Revenue or KPI Contribution section provides an analysis of the impact of your media and non-media activities on your revenue or KPI performance. It lets you compare key metrics such as return on investment (ROI), percent of spend, and percent of incremental revenue or KPI across different channels. Additionally, this section lets you break down the contribution by baseline, pricing promotions, and various marketing channels.

Baseline IMO is both control factors, but also factors not ideneified in the model. This could be branding, product quality, price, or any thing that is hard to measure. 

[https://developers.google.com/meridian/docs/user-guide/plot-media-visualizations](https://developers.google.com/meridian/docs/user-guide/plot-media-visualizations)

### Return on investment

The **Return on investment** section provides a deeper view of ROI analysis for channels to help you identify the highest performing channels. You can compare ROI, marginal ROI, and effectiveness across channels. Additionally, this section presents the credible interval for the ROI estimations, which constitutes one advantage of Bayesian models.  
![][image7]

IMO, the test data is really bad, so these are not super helpful. You will se a lot more distinction with your own data. 

Note: You can also remove the credible interval (ci) or update it to a different credible interval if that might confuse your audience. 

You can compare how each channel's return on investment (ROI) is against the channel's effectiveness by plotting ROI versus effectiveness. Effectiveness is measured by how much incremental revenue is gained per media unit. For this plot, the size of each channel maps to the level of spend. The larger the circle, the more that was spent on the channel.

You can compare the return on investment (ROI) to marginal return on investment (mROI), where mROI is the return on investment from an additional unit spent. The size of the circle maps to the amount spent on the channel. The larger the spend, the larger the circle.

**Optimal Analysis**  
The Optimal Analysis section shows your current spend level and where you start to see diminishing marginal returns on the amount of money you are spending per channel, and provides optimal frequency recommendations to help you decide how to focus your budget for the next year.

![][image8]

Response curves show your current spend level and where you start to see diminishing returns on the spending per channel.  
You can view each channels' response curves shown together in one plot or plotted independently. The shaded area of the plot shows the credible intervals while the point indicates the current spend.
